      "writtenOn": "2020-01-05T16:43:10Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "The reason we see that extra copy becomes a little clearer if you look at how these are desugared into C-like calls, given that an SkM4 is too large to return by value in registers:\n\n    setConcat(const SkM4\u0026, const SkM4\u0026) ~~\u003e setConcatC(SkM4*, const SkM4*, const SkM4*)\n\n    a.setConcat(a,b)  ~~\u003e   setConcatC(\u0026a, \u0026a, \u0026b)\n    a \u003d a * b         ~~\u003e   SkM4 tmp; setConcatC(\u0026tmp, \u0026a, \u0026b); a \u003d tmp;\n\nFor the compiler to skip the tmp matrix and turn the second line into the first, it would have to be able to prove that it is safe to alias the first and second arguments of setConcatC().  setConcatC() is out line, so there\u0027s no way it can reason about it, and I\u0027ve found no way to mark it with a hint, even on a compiler-by-compiler basis.\n\nThe a.setConcat(a,b) version has the advantage of the compiler not needing to reason at all... it just does exactly what we tell it to do, and any aliasing is on us.  If setConcat() is safe for aliasing, everything will be fine, and if not, we\u0027ll have a bug, but a bug that\u0027s our fault as programmers and not the fault of the compiler.\n\nAmusingly, we could write SkM4::operator*\u003d to be exactly as efficient as setConcat() for this sort of two-matrix math, but that won\u0027t help the general a \u003d b * c case.\n\nNow speaking of a \u003d b * c, while benchmarking we\u0027ve seen the same extra temporary copy happen when measuring a.setConcat(b,c) vs. a \u003d b * c, even where the compiler definitely could see that there\u0027s no aliasing between any of the matrices.  It certainly seems like it could take advantage of this... unclear to me whether it doesn\u0027t see it, doesn\u0027t have the ability to exploit that, doesn\u0027t care to, or I\u0027m missing something.\n\n(In case you were wondering, whether or not setConcat() returns *this or void makes no difference to any of this.  It\u0027s ~1 extra instruction that won\u0027t be on the function\u0027s critical retirement path.)",
